          Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monda=
y.We are well into the holiday season, which means that people are wrapping=
 up work for the year, and yesterday the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commi=
ssion proposed, uh, all the rules? Here are some=C2=A0new rule proposals=C2=
=A0about 10b5-1 plans, stock buybacks, money market funds and swaps. Take t=
he rest of the year off, SEC, you=E2=80=99ve earned it.=C2=A0Let=E2=80=99s =
start with swaps.
 =20
   =20
      SEC v. CDS
   =20
 =20
Here are the SEC=E2=80=99s proposed rules about =E2=80=9Csecurity-based swa=
ps.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CSwaps,=E2=80=9D to the SEC, can refer to two differen=
t instruments, which I will discuss separately. One is a credit default swa=
p, where the buyer pays a premium to the seller and the seller pays the buy=
er if some reference debt instrument =E2=80=94=C2=A0a corporate bond or loa=
n, a sovereign bond, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0defaults.=C2=A0There  was a  wave =
of controversy a few years ago  about a  category of  stuff that I will loo=
sely call =E2=80=9CCDS shenanigans.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0A credit default swap is =
a bilateral contract between two people who may or may not own any debt of =
the underlying company or=C2=A0have any relationship with the underlying co=
mpany. At some point, buyers and sellers of CDS realized that they could go=
 to the underlying company and say =E2=80=9Chey, it would help us out a lot=
 on our CDS contract if you [did][did not] default on your debt,=E2=80=9D a=
nd would cut deals with the company to do that. (=E2=80=9CDefault=E2=80=9D =
here generally meant some sort of technical default that triggered CDS but =
did not plunge the company into a disastrous bankruptcy.) Occasionally CDS =
buyers would go to the company and offer it a deal to default, and CDS sell=
ers would offer it a deal=C2=A0not=C2=A0to default, and the company could p=
lay them against each other and get itself a really good deal.This always s=
truck me as sort of wonderful. The downside was that some hedge funds lost =
money on zero-sum bets with other hedge funds. The upside was that distress=
ed companies got attractive financing to keep their businesses alive.[1] Th=
ese deals were pure transfers of money from hedge funds to workers: People =
at troubled companies got to keep their jobs because some hedge fund would =
pay their salaries in order to rip off another hedge fund.Almost nobody agr=
ees with me about this.  Literally the Pope called on hedge funds to stop g=
iving money to companies to default on their debts. Regulators have  made n=
oises forever about it being market manipulation.To me it seems like=C2=A0o=
bviously=C2=A0not market manipulation: You are not manipulating=C2=A0a mark=
et, you are changing=C2=A0economic=C2=A0reality. This is totally normal in =
distressed credit situations: A company has run out of money and might defa=
ult, which will be good for some interested parties (vulture funds who boug=
ht senior debt at a discount and want to=C2=A0seize the company,=C2=A0etc.)=
 and bad for other interested parties (junior creditors who might lose ever=
ything, etc.). Someone for whom it is bad will come to the company and say =
=E2=80=9Chey we will give you more financing so you don=E2=80=99t default a=
nd we won=E2=80=99t lose our money.=E2=80=9D Someone for whom it is good wi=
ll come to the company and say =E2=80=9Chey you should default and get out =
from these onerous debts, we will treat you nice in bankruptcy.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0The addition of CDS makes these negotiations=C2=A0more interesting but d=
oes not change the fundamental character.Again, though, nobody agrees with =
me, and the SEC wants to ban, you know, the stuff I am talking about. If th=
at sounds vague, it is. The SEC has proposed a new rule, Rule 9j-1, banning=
 manipulation of securities-based swaps. Part of this =E2=80=94=C2=A0Rule 9=
j-1(a) =E2=80=94=C2=A0basically bans market manipulation and insider tradin=
g in CDS; the SEC originally proposed this in 2010 and is coming back to it=
 now.[2] But Rule 9j-1(b) is intended to ban CDS shenanigans. From the SEC=
=E2=80=99s proposal:Re-proposed Rule 9j-1(b) would make it unlawful for any=
 person to, directly or indirectly, manipulate or attempt to manipulate the=
 price or valuation of any security-based swap, or any payment or delivery =
related thereto. Among other things, this language is intended to address a=
 number of the manufactured or other opportunistic CDS strategies observed =
over the last decade, and summarized above in section I.B, including situat=
ions where a party intentionally distorts any payment related to a security=
-based swap for the benefit of one of the security-based swap counterpartie=
s, such as actions that serve little to no economic purpose other than to a=
rtificially influence the composition of the deliverable obligations in a C=
DS auction.Re-proposed Rule 9j-1(b) also is intended to prohibit, among oth=
er things, a situation where a person (or group of persons) improperly and =
intentionally causes or avoids the purchase or sale of a security-based swa=
p for the benefit of a counterparty to an SBS, such as intentionally and im=
properly orphaning a CDS, avoiding termination of a CDS for a period of tim=
e, or causing the termination of a CDS. As previously noted, =E2=80=9Corpha=
ning=E2=80=9D a CDS refers to a situation where the debt of a reference ent=
ity is eliminated or reduced for the purposes of moving the price of CDS.=
=C2=A0The end result of such activity is that CDS buyers continue to pay (a=
nd CDS sellers continue to receive) premiums on CDS that will never default=
. Similarly, a CDS protection seller could offer financing to the company t=
o avoid a credit event and subsequent CDS payout, with the financing timed =
so that the company=E2=80=99s bankruptcy is merely delayed until after the =
CDS expires.=C2=A0To be clear, a person simply profiting from a CDS positio=
n after a company=E2=80=99s bankruptcy, which such person could have preven=
ted by participating in a financing to the company, without more is not in =
and of itself improper conduct for purposes of re-proposed Rule 9j-1(b).Tha=
t last sentence is fun. You are a big credit fund, you own CDS on a company=
 and you will make money if it goes bankrupt. The company comes to you and =
says =E2=80=9Cwill you lend us some money to avoid bankruptcy?=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9CNo,=E2=80=9D you say, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll be better off if you go b=
ankrupt.=E2=80=9D Is that CDS manipulation? No, says the SEC. Or rather, =
=E2=80=9Cwithout more,=E2=80=9D it =E2=80=9Cis not in and of itself imprope=
r conduct.=E2=80=9DAlternatively: You are a big credit fund, you have=C2=A0=
sold=C2=A0CDS on a company, and you will lose money if it goes bankrupt. Th=
e company comes to you and says =E2=80=9Cwill you lend us some money to avo=
id bankruptcy?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CSure,=E2=80=9D you say, =E2=80=9Cthat way =
I will save money on my CDS trade.=E2=80=9D Is that CDS manipulation? I mea=
n, probably not, but it=E2=80=99s a live question now isn=E2=80=99t it?=C2=
=A0Are you =E2=80=9Cimproperly and intentionally ... avoiding termination o=
