The other thing that the SEC counts as a =E2=80=9Cswap=E2=80=9D is what I w=
ill loosely call an =E2=80=9Cequity total return swap.=E2=80=9D[4] This is =
a contract in which an investment bank buys a bunch of stock of some compan=
y=C2=A0on behalf of=C2=A0the bank=E2=80=99s client, generally a hedge fund.=
 The bank holds the stock; if it goes up, the bank pays money to the client=
; if it goes down, the client pays money to the bank. The client has econom=
ic exposure to the stock (it makes money when it goes up and loses money wh=
en it goes down); the bank mostly does not (it is perfectly hedged unless t=
he client defaults).There are two main reasons a client would do this. One =
is leverage. If you want to buy $1 billion of stock but don=E2=80=99t have =
$1 billion lying around, you can buy it =E2=80=9Con swap,=E2=80=9D the=C2=
=A0bank=C2=A0will put up the $1 billion, and you=E2=80=99ll only have to pu=
t down a deposit of $100 million or $200 million or whatever to cover the r=
isk that you=E2=80=99ll have to pay the bank when the stock moves down. Thi=
s is roughly equivalent to a margin loan =E2=80=94=C2=A0the bank lends you =
some of the money to buy the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is a little nicer =
for the bank,[5] so the bank will be willing to give you more leverage on b=
etter terms.The other is, sometimes the client wants to own the stock but n=
ot, you know,=C2=A0own=C2=A0the stock. There are various rules that apply t=
o owners of stock that those owners might find annoying, and if you just wa=
nt to have economic exposure to a stock you might buy it on swap and skip t=
he legal ownership. The most obvious of these rules, in the U.S., is Sectio=
n 13=C2=A0of the Exchange Act: If you own a lot of stock of a company, you =
have to disclose your ownership, which you might not want to do. If you own=
 the stock on swap, your=C2=A0banks=C2=A0might have to disclose their owner=
ship, or they might not,[6] but there=E2=80=99s no public indication that=
=C2=A0you=C2=A0are the economic owner. To be clear, there is a reason for t=
his: Section 13 is meant to let people know who owns a company, and if you =
own shares on swap you don=E2=80=99t. You can=E2=80=99t vote those shares. =
You don=E2=80=99t have control the way a big actual shareholder would. You =
just have an economic bet on the stock.Similarly, there are antitrust appro=
val rules that apply to people who acquire big chunks of stock, and if you =
want to buy stock economically without jumping through antitrust hoops, you=
 might buy on swap. (And because you can=E2=80=99t control the company with=
 a swap, it doesn=E2=80=99t count.) Or there are ownership restrictions in =
various industries, like banking, that  swaps might get around.This strikes=
 me as mostly fine?=C2=A0The broad theme is that there are a lot of rules d=
esigned to get at=C2=A0ownership=C2=A0and=C2=A0control=C2=A0of companies, a=
nd buying stock on swap is a way to get=C2=A0economic exposure=C2=A0to comp=
anies without ownership or control. So all the rules about ownership and co=
ntrol don=E2=80=99t apply to swaps. Everything sort of works as designed.Bu=
t=C2=A0the somewhat weird result is that swaps seem to evade=C2=A0every=C2=
=A0disclosure regime, because all the disclosure rules are aimed at ownersh=
ip, and swaps are not ownership, and there is no separate swaps disclosure =
rule. Now the SEC has proposed one:The Commission has decided to utilize it=
s rulemaking authority under Section 10B of the Exchange Act to propose new=
 Rule 10B-1, which would be a large trader position reporting rule for secu=
rity-based swaps. Specifically, proposed Rule 10B-1 would require public re=
porting of, among other things: (1) certain large positions in security-bas=
ed swaps; (2) positions in any security or loan underlying the security-bas=
ed swap position; and (3) positions in any other instrument relating to the=
 underlying security or loan or group or index of securities or loans. As d=
escribed in detail below, proposed Rule 10B-1 would, among other things, in=
clude a specific quantitative threshold for when public reporting is requir=
ed. ...In terms of timing, proposed Rule 10B-1(a)(2) would provide that any=
 Schedule 10B required by the rule shall be filed promptly, but in no event=
 later than the end of the first business day following the day of executio=
n of the security-based swap transaction that results in the Security-Based=
 Swap Position first exceeding the Reporting Threshold Amount.The Reporting=
 Threshold Amount, for stock total return swaps, is either $300 million of =
notional amount or 5% of the company=E2=80=99s stock.[7] Under the proposed=
 rules, if you own a lot of stock on swap, you=E2=80=99ll have to disclose =
it.One reason people want a rule like this is that, because swap positions =
are generally not subject to disclosure obligations, nobody knows about the=
m, and so big secret risks can build up in the financial system.The poster =
child for this is Archegos Capital Management, a family office that had a b=
unch of huge stock positions on swap; the stocks went down, Archegos defaul=
ted on the swaps, and its banks sold all the stocks quickly, leading to big=
 price moves. In the early days of  the Archegos story, it was widely belie=
ved that the banks=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t know about each others=E2=80=99 swap=
s:=C2=A0Each bank knew =E2=80=9CI own 2% of this stock for Archegos,=E2=80=
=9D but not =E2=80=9Cfive other banks do too and there=E2=80=99s a ton of s=
tock to sell if Archegos goes bust.=E2=80=9D But that turned out to be comp=
letely untrue. Credit Suisse Group AG, which lost billions of dollars on Ar=
chegos,  published a very thorough and embarrassing report about its failin=
gs, and one clear conclusion of the report is that Credit Suisse=C2=A0absol=
utely=C2=A0knew about Archegos=E2=80=99s positions with other banks. Archeg=
os=E2=80=99s banks had various risk management problems, but =E2=80=9Cswaps=
 are secret=E2=80=9D does not seem to have been one of them.On the other ha=
nd it is true that=C2=A0journalists, and=C2=A0the SEC, and=C2=A0other share=
holders, didn=E2=80=99t know about Archegos=E2=80=99s huge swap positions. =
I do not know what they would have done if they had known but, yes, conceiv=
ably someone might have said =E2=80=9Chey Archegos are you sure you want to=
 own so much of those stocks=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Chey banks are you sure yo=
u all want to be financing such big positions for Archegos=E2=80=9D or what=
ever. So more swap disclosure might have helped there.The other objection t=
o total return swaps comes from=C2=A0public companies who worry about activ=
ist investors. The basic thing an activist investor traditionally does is (=
1) quietly buy up a big stake in a company, (2) announce that she owns a=C2=
=A0stake and (3) pressure the company to do stuff. Public companies do not =
like to be pressured to do stuff, so they tend to dislike activists. One li=
ne of attack that corporate managers take against activists is to try to li=
mit their ability to quietly buy up big stakes in companies. Activists like=
 to buy stakes quietly because, once they announce that they own a big chun=
k of stock in a company and plan to do activism, the stock will generally g=
o up.[8] If the rules said =E2=80=9Cas soon as an activist even thinks abou=
t buying stock, she has to disclose that, so everyone knows what she=E2=80=
=99s doing,=E2=80=9D then the stock will go up=C2=A0before=C2=A0she buys, a=
nd being an activist will be less economically viable. All of the benefits =
of her activism =E2=80=94=C2=A0her ability to push the company to do better=
 things for shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0will go, prospectively, to the peop=
le who=C2=A0sell=C2=A0her the stock, not to her.Right now the main rule abo=
ut this in U.S. law is Section 13(d) of the Exchange Act, which says that i=
nvestors have to disclose their stakes, and any activist intentions, on Sch=
edule 13D, within=C2=A010 days after they get above 5% of the stock.=C2=A0T=
his gives activists a chance to buy, you know, 8% or so of the stock quietl=
y, before disclosing it 10 days after they cross the 5% threshold.=C2=A0(Th=
ere is also Section 13(f), which says that institutional investment manager=
s have to disclose all of their large positions every quarter.) Corporate m=
anagers would prefer a shorter deadline to make life harder for activists. =
(My old law firm, Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz, does a lot of activism de=
fense, and has been pushing for this for more than a decade.)Activists some=
times use swaps to build larger economic positions without triggering 13D r=
equirements, and so swap disclosure is a way to restrict activists. Right n=
ow, Section 13(d) requires disclosure only of =E2=80=9Cbeneficial ownership=
=E2=80=9D of stock, and most swaps =E2=80=94 cash-settled bets on stock pri=
ces =E2=80=94=C2=A0do not carry beneficial ownership and don=E2=80=99t trig=
ger disclosure requirements. Again, this fits with what the 13D rules are=
=C2=A0intended=C2=A0to do, which is require disclosure of big voting positi=
ons. But people worry that activists who buy stock on swap can quickly exch=
ange their swaps for =E2=80=9Cphysical=E2=80=9D positions in voting stock. =
(For instance, by buying the stock from the bank that is holding it as a he=
dge to their swap.) Or they worry that the activist=E2=80=99s swap counterp=
arties (the banks) will feel pressure to vote the stock the way the activis=
t wants. Or they just want everyone to know that an activist is acquiring s=
tock, on swap or otherwise, so that retail investors can copy the activists=
