The  basic issue is that if you are a senior executive of a public company,=
 (1) you always know things about the company that the public doesn=E2=80=
=99t know, but (2) we want you to be able to trade stock anyway. Everyone l=
oves when corporate executives=C2=A0buy=C2=A0stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0bullish s=
ignal, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and, since lots of executives are paid mostly in=
 stock, we want them to be able to sell stock sometimes to buy houses and s=
tuff.So there are rules and norms that let executives trade stock without g=
etting in trouble for insider trading. One is the norm that there are =E2=
=80=9Copen windows=E2=80=9D for trading, typically shortly after a company =
announces earnings; the idea is that the company has disclosed everything m=
aterial in the earnings release and call, so now the executives don=E2=80=
=99t know any more than anyone else and can trade freely. (This is mostly s=
illy but nonetheless the norm.[9]) The other is Rule 10b5-1(c), which says =
that if an executive sets up an automated=C2=A0plan to trade stock while sh=
e has no material nonpublic information (i.e. when she is in an open window=
), that=C2=A0plan=C2=A0can go ahead and trade stock for her even if she lat=
er gets some material nonpublic information.Rule 10b5-1 plans are controver=
sial. For one thing, it is  theoretically possible to game them to insider =
trade in cute but somewhat silly ways.=C2=A0More important, though, nobody=
=C2=A0really=C2=A0believes that executives are ever free of inside informat=
ion, so the whole 10b5-1 concept seems suspect. If you set up a plan to tra=
de stock, and then a week later you sell stock, and then a week later bad n=
ews comes out and=C2=A0the stock goes down, everyone will say =E2=80=9Cwell=
 you probably had inside information didn=E2=80=99t you.=E2=80=9DOne really=
 simple fix here would be to say: Okay, executives can trade stock all they=
 want, but on a long delay. You can put in an order today saying =E2=80=9Cs=
ell 10,000 shares,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Csell $50,000 of stock,=E2=80=9D and=
 your broker can execute it, but only=C2=A0four months from now. You might =
have inside information today, and you might have inside information in fou=
r months, but=C2=A0it will definitely be different information. If you want=
 to sell stock today because you have secret knowledge of a data breach or =
an earnings miss, or you want to buy stock today because you have secret kn=
owledge of a merger or an earnings beat, just put in the order today, trade=
 in four months, and by then the market will have already learned and price=
d in whatever secret information you know today and moved on to other thing=
s.The simple and elegant solution would be to have a new rule saying=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Ccorporate executives can put in an order to trade=C2=A0stock whene=
ver they want, whether or not they have inside information, but the order c=
an=E2=80=99t execute for four months and can=E2=80=99t be canceled in the m=
eantime.=E2=80=9D But I guess that=E2=80=99s a bit harsh and weird, and any=
way Rule 10b5-1 already exists, so the SEC did not take that approach. Inst=
ead:The proposed amendments to Rule 10b5-1 would update the requirements fo=
r the affirmative defense, including imposing a cooling off period before t=
rading could commence under a plan, prohibiting overlapping trading plans, =
and limiting single-trade plans to one trading plan per twelve month period=
. In addition, the proposed rules would require directors and officers to f=
urnish written certifications that they are not aware of any material nonpu=
blic information when they enter into the plans and expand the existing goo=
d faith requirement for trading under Rule 10b5-1 plans.=E2=80=9CSpecifical=
ly,=E2=80=9D says the SEC, =E2=80=9Cour proposals would:=C2=A0Require a Rul=
e 10b5-1 trading arrangement entered into by officers or directors to inclu=
de a 120-day mandatory cooling-off period before any trading can commence u=
nder the trading arrangement after its adoption (including adoption of a mo=
dified trading arrangement).=E2=80=9D (The=C2=A0company itself=C2=A0can do =
a 10b5-1 plan, for a stock buyback, with a 30-day cooling-off period.) Seem=
s reasonable.=C2=A0There are a bunch of other new 10b5-1 rules,[10]=C2=A0of=
 which my favorite is the one that will =E2=80=9Cprovide that the affirmati=
ve defense under Rule 10b5-1(c)(1) does not apply to multiple overlapping R=
ule 10b5=E2=80=911 trading arrangements for open market trades in the same =
class of securities.=E2=80=9D The classic cutesy securities-lawyer hypothet=
ical way to game Rule 10b5-1 is:=09You don=E2=80=99t have inside informatio=
n now, but you are sure you will in five=C2=A0months. (For instance, you=E2=
=80=99ll announce earnings in 5.5 months; in five months you=E2=80=99ll kno=
w what=E2=80=99s in the earnings but the market won=E2=80=99t.)=09Set up a =
10b5-1 plan, today, to sell a bunch of stock in five months.=09Set up anoth=
er 10b5-1 plan, today, to buy a bunch of stock in five months.=09Wait five =
months and get the inside information.=09If you have good inside informatio=
n, cancel the selling plan but leave the buying one in place. You=E2=80=99l=
l buy stock, the information will come out, the stock will go up.=09If you =
have bad inside information, cancel the buying plan but leave the selling o=
ne in place. You=E2=80=99ll sell stock, the information will come out, the =
stock will go down.The idea is that canceling=C2=A0a 10b5-1 plan is not a =
=E2=80=9Ctrade=E2=80=9D and so you can do it even if you have inside inform=
ation. This is very cute but I cannot imagine anyone really does it, and I =
am pretty sure it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0illegal under existing law. Nonetheless th=
