People are worried about stock buybacks? The SEC has proposed new stock buy=
back disclosure rules,[11] some of which are about making companies disclos=
e stock buybacks on a more timely and comprehensive basis. There will be a =
new =E2=80=9CForm SR,=E2=80=9D and companies will have to file it within a =
day after buying back stock, disclosing how many shares they purchased and =
how much they paid. Currently companies disclose this on a long lag in thei=
r quarterly reports; the SEC wants to make that disclosure daily.But anothe=
r weird part of the rules is that companies will now have to disclose=C2=A0=
why=C2=A0they bought back stock. (In their quarterly reports, not in the da=
ily Form SR.) There are, I think, roughly four overlapping good reasons for=
 a company to buy back stock:=09We have a lot of cash and no good investmen=
t ideas, so we=E2=80=99re going to hand it back to shareholders for them to=
 figure out what to do with it.=09We have a lot of cash and our shareholder=
s could use some cash, so we=E2=80=99re going to give them some of ours.=09=
Our stock price is too low so we=E2=80=99re going to buy some to improve re=
turns for our remaining shareholders.=09We have too much equity in our capi=
tal structure so we are going to raise debt and buy back stock to improve o=
ur return on equity.[12]But people who are worried about stock buybacks thi=
nk that companies do them for bad reasons, such as:=09To manipulate earning=
s per share calculations by reducing the share count.=09To artificially inf=
late the stock price.=09To artificially inflate the stock price so that exe=
cutives can sell stock while the company buys.=09To cover up the massive di=
lution caused by executive stock grants.=09Etc.The SEC=E2=80=99s proposed=
=C2=A0rules would basically require companies to declare that they=E2=80=99=
re not doing any of the bad reasons:Specifically, we propose to require an =
issuer to disclose:=E2=80=A2 The objective or rationale for its share repur=
chases and process or criteria used to determine the amount of repurchases;=
=E2=80=A2 Any policies and procedures relating to purchases and sales of th=
e issuer=E2=80=99s securities by its officers and directors during a repurc=
hase program, including any restriction on such transactions. ...We are add=
itionally proposing to require that issuers disclose if any of their office=
rs or directors =E2=80=A6 purchased or sold shares =E2=80=A6 within 10 busi=
ness days before or after=C2=A0the announcement of an issuer purchase plan =
or program by checking a box.I feel like =E2=80=9Cthe objective or rational=
e for its share repurchases=E2=80=9D is going to get real formulaic real qu=
ick? Part of the point here is just to make it a tiny bit more annoying for=
 companies to buy back stock by making them type this somewhat embarrassing=
 formulaic declaration.But part of the point is of course that  everything =
is securities fraud. Now companies will need to say, in their securities fi=
lings, that they are buying back stock for good reasons and not to enrich t=
heir executives. And now disgruntled shareholders will be able to sue, sayi=
ng =E2=80=9Cactually you bought back stock to enrich your executives and li=
ed about it in your securities filings.=E2=80=9D
