      Things happen
   =20
 =20
Reddit  Files for IPO After Igniting the Year=E2=80=99s Meme Stock Frenzy. =
Private Equity Firm  TPG Files for Long-Awaited U.S. IPO. WallStreetBets Jo=
kes of  Pumping Reddit Stock After IPO Filing. Anchorage Capital Is Closing=
 $7.4 Billion Flagship Hedge Fund. Money Manager  Vanishes With $313 Millio=
n From China Builder. JPMorgan A-Rod Adviser  Loses Ruling in Client-Poachi=
ng Fight. Fired JPMorgan Trader Shows It Pays to  Win Your Old Job Back. UK=
 regulator fines GAM and former star fund manager over managing Gupta ties.=
 US borrowers breach loan limit guidance at record pace. Michael Jordan Jum=
ps Into Web3 via Solana App for Athletes. Tesla Takes Customers to Court to=
  Silence Its Critics in China. Harvard scam. =E2=80=9CSomeone was walking =
through the streets with black bin liners of cash.=E2=80=9D Drawing bought =
for $30 at estate sale is actually worth $50 million. Kraft will pay you $2=
0 not to make cheesecake for Christmas. Melania Trump Joins Crypto Frenzy W=
ith Release of First  NFT.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0i=
n handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link=
. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters=
 here. Thanks![1] The other downside, to be fair, is that some distressed c=
ompanies probably *should* shut down their businesses, and CDS shenanigans =
could keep them alive inefficiently.[2] Arguably this has not been a priori=
ty because insider trading and market manipulation in CDS is probably illeg=
al anyway. =E2=80=9CAlthough the Commission generally believes that a situa=
tion where a person uses material non-public information in a security in c=
onnection with the purchase and sale of a security-based swap would be subj=
ect to the existing antifraud authority under the Federal securities laws, =
particularly Section 10(b) of the Exchange Act and Rule 10b-5 thereunder, t=
he Commission also believes that market participants would benefit from a c=
larified interpretation of that statutory provision in this rulemaking,=E2=
=80=9D says the SEC.[3] This feels a little weird in modern syndicated loan=
 markets, but some residue of it still exists. See page 28 of this 2016 Dav=
is Polk memo for an overview of how lenders treat the =E2=80=9Cpublic side=
=E2=80=9D/=E2=80=9Cprivate side=E2=80=9D distinction in loan markets.[4] Lo=
osely because in practice you can do a number of economically very similar =
transactions with different names. =E2=80=9CTotal return swap=E2=80=9D feel=
s like the most standard and generic, but =E2=80=9Cforward=E2=80=9D or =E2=
=80=9Cpenny-strike call option=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cput/call combo=E2=80=9D=
 all mean more or less the same thing, and you can put =E2=80=9Ccash settle=
d=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cphysically settled=E2=80=9D in front of any of those=
 things to get economically similar but technologically different transacti=
ons. Also you can more or less lump any sort of high-delta option transacti=
on into this bucket too. The category is =E2=80=9Cleveraged synthetic expos=
ure to a stock,=E2=80=9D which I will just generically call =E2=80=9Ctotal =
return swaps.=E2=80=9D[5] In a margin loan you own the stock, the bank has =
a lien on it, and foreclosing can be a bit complicated and annoying. In a s=
wap the bank owns the stock and can just sell it whenever it wants, and it =
can close out the swap=C2=A0under contractual terms that are probably very =
protective of the bank.[6] The main Section 13(d) threshold is 5%. Iff you =
own 5% on swap with five different banks, and none of them is above 5% itse=
lf, then they won=E2=80=99t.[7] This reporting rule also covers CDS, at a l=
ower threshold, and is intended to crack down on =E2=80=9Cnet short debt ac=
tivism=E2=80=9D along the lines of (allegedly) the Aurelius/Windstream situ=
ation.=C2=A0[8] If they=E2=80=99re good activists anyway.[9] To be clear, i=
t is just a default norm. If the executives are negotiating a merger or dea=
ling with a huge data breach right after earnings, and they trade the stock=
, that can still be insider trading.[10]=C2=A0The other complaint that peop=
le sometimes make about 10b5-1 plans is that they should be disclosed in ad=
vance; executives should have to give shareholders some warning that they m=
ight be buying or selling stock. The SEC=E2=80=99s proposed rules don=E2=80=
=99t say that, but they would=C2=A0require companies to provide new quarter=
ly disclosures about whether any officers or directors have put in place (o=
r canceled) a 10b5-1 plan, and how long it will last and how many shares it=
 covers.=C2=A0[11] It=E2=80=99s not in these rules, but we talked in the pr=
evious section about the new proposed cooling-off period under Rule 10b5-1.=
 Companies that do open-market stock buybacks often do so under Rule 10b5-1=
, so that they can set up an automatic buyback plan and continue buying thr=
ough blackout periods. The new Rule 10b5-1 proposal would require them to w=
ait 30 days after setting up the plan before they start buying. (I think a =
fair number of companies do this anyway, to be safe, but now it might be re=
quired.)[12] Everyone in finance thinks this is a good reason to buy back s=
tock (except Modigliani and Miller, ha), but normal people hate it. Nonethe=
less I am counting it as a good reason.[13] Exercise for the reader: What d=
o you think are the margins on this product? My guess is =E2=80=9Csurprisin=
gly low, depending on how you count.=E2=80=9D
