d-color: #ccc;">the SEC=E2=80=99s proposal</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Re-proposed Rule 9j-1(b) would make it unlawful for any pe=
rson to, directly or indirectly, manipulate or attempt to manipulate the pr=
ice or valuation of any security-based swap, or any payment or delivery rel=
ated thereto. Among other things, this language is intended to address a nu=
mber of the manufactured or other opportunistic CDS strategies observed ove=
r the last decade, and summarized above in section I.B, including situation=
s where a party intentionally distorts any payment related to a security-ba=
sed swap for the benefit of one of the security-based swap counterparties, =
such as actions that serve little to no economic purpose other than to arti=
ficially influence the composition of the deliverable obligations in a CDS =
auction.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Re-proposed Rule 9j-1(b) also is i=
ntended to prohibit, among other things, a situation where a person (or gro=
up of persons) improperly and intentionally causes or avoids the purchase o=
r sale of a security-based swap for the benefit of a counterparty to an SBS=
, such as intentionally and improperly orphaning a CDS, avoiding terminatio=
n of a CDS for a period of time, or causing the termination of a CDS. As pr=
eviously noted, =E2=80=9Corphaning=E2=80=9D a CDS refers to a situation whe=
re the debt of a reference entity is eliminated or reduced for the purposes=
 of moving the price of CDS.=C2=A0The end result of such activity is that C=
DS buyers continue to pay (and CDS sellers continue to receive) premiums on=
 CDS that will never default. Similarly, a CDS protection seller could offe=
r financing to the company to avoid a credit event and subsequent CDS payou=
t, with the financing timed so that the company=E2=80=99s bankruptcy is mer=
ely delayed until after the CDS expires.=C2=A0To be clear, a person simply =
profiting from a CDS position after a company=E2=80=99s bankruptcy, which s=
uch person could have prevented by participating in a financing to the comp=
any, without more is not in and of itself improper conduct for purposes of =
re-proposed Rule 9j-1(b).</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=
 last sentence is fun. You are a big credit fund, you own CDS on a company =
and you will make money if it goes bankrupt. The company comes to you and s=
ays =E2=80=9Cwill you lend us some money to avoid bankruptcy?=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9CNo,=E2=80=9D you say, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll be better off if you go b=
ankrupt.=E2=80=9D Is that CDS manipulation? No, says the SEC. Or rather, =
=E2=80=9Cwithout more,=E2=80=9D it =E2=80=9Cis not in and of itself imprope=
r conduct.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alternatively: You are =
a big credit fund, you have=C2=A0<em>sold=C2=A0</em>CDS on a company, and y=
ou will lose money if it goes bankrupt. The company comes to you and says =
=E2=80=9Cwill you lend us some money to avoid bankruptcy?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=9CSure,=E2=80=9D you say, =E2=80=9Cthat way I will save money on my CDS tr=
ade.=E2=80=9D Is that CDS manipulation? I mean, probably not, but it=E2=80=
=99s a live question now isn=E2=80=99t it?=C2=A0Are you =E2=80=9Cimproperly=
 and intentionally ... avoiding termination of a CDS for a period of time=
=E2=80=9D? Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/26067671.278641/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9ydWxlcy9wcm9wb3NlZC8yMDI=
