-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> =E2=80=9Corphaning=E2=80=9D the ol=
d CDS</a>: When all the debt of the old financing subsidiary is gone, the C=
DS on that subsidiary is worthless; you sold that CDS and have a windfall w=
hen it becomes worthless. That=E2=80=99s the thing the SEC wants to prevent=
. But which part of what you are doing =E2=80=9Cappears to be designed almo=
st exclusively to harm one or more CDS counterparties=E2=80=9D? Which part =
is just =E2=80=9Cthe ordinary course of a typical lender-borrower relations=
hip=E2=80=9D?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s also worth brief=
ly discussing Rule 9j-1(a), which is meant (among other things) to prohibit=
 insider trading in CDS. CDS was originally designed as a way for banks to =
hedge their credit risk in lending: A bank would lend money to a company, a=
nd then it would buy CDS in the market to insure it against credit losses o=
n the loan.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Classically, a bank loan is not=
 a =E2=80=9Csecurity,=E2=80=9D and it is okay =E2=80=94=C2=A0expected, real=
ly =E2=80=94=C2=A0for a bank to make loans while it has material nonpublic =
information about the borrower. Classically banks are trusted partners of t=
heir borrower companies; the companies tell them everything, and the banks =
know the borrowers really well so they=C2=A0can make good credit decisions.=
[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These things interact awkwardly. If you=
=E2=80=99re a bank and you lend money to a company based on inside informat=
ion, and then you hedge in the CDS market, are you committing insider tradi=
ng? I think the answer is and should be =E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D: =E2=80=9CBan=
ks are best positioned to evaluate credit risk because they have total acce=
ss to a company=E2=80=9D is a reasonable theory of banking, and =E2=80=9Cba=
nks fund loans but hedge the credit risk in the CDS market=E2=80=9D is a re=
asonable theory of banking, but=C2=A0<em>they make no sense together</em>. =
Either get inside information and own the credit risk, or use public inform=
ation and hedge in public markets. This seems pretty obvious, and the SEC=
=C2=A0 apparently agrees, but they asked for comments in case anyone disagr=
ees:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Should the Commission also=
 create a safe harbor for entering into security-based swap transactions fo=
r purposes of hedging some or all of their exposure arising out of lending =
activities with a reference entity or the syndication of such lending activ=
ities? Why or why not? If such a safe harbor is necessary, should =E2=80=9C=
hedging=E2=80=9D be defined and if so, how should it be defined? What types=
 of activities should be included and/or excluded in such a safe harbor? Wh=
at conditions should be included to protect other market participants and t=
o ensure that any such safe harbor is not overly broad? For example, should=
 the safe harbor require that a person using a security-based swap to hedge=
 their interest in a loan while in possession of material nonpublic informa=
tion provide certain information to their counterparty about the underlying=
 borrower/reference entity? If so, what information should be required to b=
e provided, and why? Should the safe harbor be conditioned on the person us=
ing a security-based swap to hedge their interest in a loan being a particu=
lar type of financial institution, such as a bank?</p></blockquote><table c=
