<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SEC v. TRS</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other thing that the SEC counts as=
 a =E2=80=9Cswap=E2=80=9D is what I will loosely call an =E2=80=9Cequity to=
tal return swap.=E2=80=9D[4] This is a contract in which an investment bank=
 buys a bunch of stock of some company=C2=A0<em>on behalf of=C2=A0</em>the =
bank=E2=80=99s client, generally a hedge fund. The bank holds the stock; if=
 it goes up, the bank pays money to the client; if it goes down, the client=
 pays money to the bank. The client has economic exposure to the stock (it =
makes money when it goes up and loses money when it goes down); the bank mo=
stly does not (it is perfectly hedged unless the client defaults).</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two main reasons a client would do this. =
One is leverage. If you want to buy $1 billion of stock but don=E2=80=99t h=
ave $1 billion lying around, you can buy it =E2=80=9Con swap,=E2=80=9D the=
=C2=A0<em>bank=C2=A0</em>will put up the $1 billion, and you=E2=80=99ll onl=
y have to put down a deposit of $100 million or $200 million or whatever to=
 cover the risk that you=E2=80=99ll have to pay the bank when the stock mov=
es down. This is roughly equivalent to a margin loan =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ban=
k lends you some of the money to buy the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is a l=
ittle nicer for the bank,[5] so the bank will be willing to give you more l=
everage on better terms.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other is, some=
times the client wants to own the stock but not, you know,=C2=A0<em>own=C2=
=A0</em>the stock. There are various rules that apply to owners of stock th=
at those owners might find annoying, and if you just want to have economic =
exposure to a stock you might buy it on swap and skip the legal ownership. =
The most obvious of these rules, in the U.S., is Section 13=C2=A0of the Exc=
hange Act: If you own a lot of stock of a company, you have to disclose you=
r ownership, which you might not want to do. If you own the stock on swap, =
your=C2=A0<em>banks=C2=A0</em>might have to disclose their ownership, or th=
ey might not,[6] but there=E2=80=99s no public indication that=C2=A0<em>you=
=C2=A0</em>are the economic owner. To be clear, there is a <em>reason</em> =
for this: Section 13 is meant to let people know who owns a company, and if=
 you own shares on swap you don=E2=80=99t. You can=E2=80=99t vote those sha=
res. You don=E2=80=99t have control the way a big actual shareholder would.=
 You just have an economic bet on the stock.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Similarly, there are antitrust approval rules that apply to people who ac=
quire big chunks of stock, and if you want to buy stock economically withou=
t jumping through antitrust hoops, you might buy on swap. (And because you =
can=E2=80=99t control the company with a swap, it doesn=E2=80=99t count.) O=
r there are ownership restrictions in various industries, like banking, tha=
t <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26067671.278641/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMTcvYmlsbC1=
od2FuZy1tYWRlLXNlY3JldC1iYW5rLWJldC1iZWZvcmUtMjAtYmlsbGlvbi1sb3NzLWFyY2hlZ2=
9zLWNvbGxhcHNlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMTYyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmd=
XRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTIxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlz=
dHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbaf12c42" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> swaps might get around<=
/a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This strikes me as mostly fine?=C2=A0T=
he broad theme is that there are a lot of rules designed to get at=C2=A0<em=
>ownership=C2=A0</em>and=C2=A0<em>control=C2=A0</em>of companies, and buyin=
g stock on swap is a way to get=C2=A0<em>economic exposure</em>=C2=A0to com=
panies without ownership or control. So all the rules about ownership and c=
ontrol don=E2=80=99t apply to swaps. Everything sort of works as designed.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=C2=A0the somewhat weird result is that =
swaps seem to evade=C2=A0<em>every=C2=A0</em>disclosure regime, because all=
 the disclosure rules are aimed at ownership, and swaps are not ownership, =
and there is no separate swaps disclosure rule. Now the SEC has <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26067671.278641/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuc2VjLmdvdi9ydWxlcy9wcm9wb3NlZC8yMDIxLzM0LTkzNzg0LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cE40639b89" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">proposed one</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">The Commission has decided to utilize its rulemaking authority=
 under Section 10B of the Exchange Act to propose new Rule 10B-1, which wou=
ld be a large trader position reporting rule for security-based swaps. Spec=
ifically, proposed Rule 10B-1 would require public reporting of, among othe=
r things: (1) certain large positions in security-based swaps; (2) position=
s in any security or loan underlying the security-based swap position; and =
(3) positions in any other instrument relating to the underlying security o=
r loan or group or index of securities or loans. As described in detail bel=
ow, proposed Rule 10B-1 would, among other things, include a specific quant=
itative threshold for when public reporting is required. ...</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">In terms of timing, proposed Rule 10B-1(a)(2) would provi=
de that any Schedule 10B required by the rule shall be filed promptly, but =
in no event later than the end of the first business day following the day =
of execution of the security-based swap transaction that results in the Sec=
urity-Based Swap Position first exceeding the Reporting Threshold Amount.</=
p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Reporting Threshold Amount,=
 for stock total return swaps, is either $300 million of notional amount or=
 5% of the company=E2=80=99s stock.[7] Under the proposed rules, if you own=
 a lot of stock on swap, you=E2=80=99ll have to disclose it.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">One reason people want a rule like this is that, because =
swap positions are generally not subject to disclosure obligations, nobody =
knows about them, and so big secret risks can build up in the financial sys=
tem.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The poster child for this is Archegos =
Capital Management, a family office that had a bunch of huge stock position=
s on swap; the stocks went down, Archegos defaulted on the swaps, and its b=
anks sold all the stocks quickly, leading to big price moves. In the early =
days of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26067671.2=
78641/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtM=
DUvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1zLWFyY2hlZ29zLXN3YXAtYWZ0ZXJtYXRoLWlzLWF3a3dhcmQtZm9yLWJh=
bmtzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMTYyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJ=
jZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTIxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe7019a03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the Archegos story</a>, it was wid=
ely believed that the banks=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t know about each others=
=E2=80=99 swaps:=C2=A0</em>Each bank knew =E2=80=9CI own 2% of this stock f=
or Archegos,=E2=80=9D but not =E2=80=9Cfive other banks do too and there=E2=
=80=99s a ton of stock to sell if Archegos goes bust.=E2=80=9D But that tur=
ned out to be completely untrue. Credit Suisse Group AG, which lost billion=
s of dollars on Archegos, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/26067671.278641/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjkvYXJjaGVnb3Mtd2FzLXRvby1idXN5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM_Y2=
1waWQ9QkJEMTIxNjIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld=
3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMjE2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB0f71f08e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> published a very thorough and embarrassing=
 report</a> about its failings, and one clear conclusion of the report is t=
hat Credit Suisse=C2=A0<em>absolutely=C2=A0</em>knew about Archegos=E2=80=
=99s positions with other banks. Archegos=E2=80=99s banks had various risk =
management problems, but =E2=80=9Cswaps are secret=E2=80=9D does not seem t=
o have been one of them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand =
it is true that=C2=A0<em>journalists</em>, and=C2=A0<em>the SEC</em>, and=
=C2=A0<em>other shareholders</em>, didn=E2=80=99t know about Archegos=E2=80=
=99s huge swap positions. I do not know what they would have done if they h=
ad known but, yes, conceivably someone might have said =E2=80=9Chey Archego=
s are you sure you want to own so much of those stocks=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9Chey banks are you sure you all want to be financing such big positions f=
or Archegos=E2=80=9D or whatever. So more swap disclosure might have helped=
 there.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other objection to total return=
 swaps comes from=C2=A0<em>public companies</em> who worry about <em>activi=
st investors</em>. The basic thing an activist investor traditionally does =
is (1) quietly buy up a big stake in a company, (2) announce that she owns =
a=C2=A0stake and (3) pressure the company to do stuff. Public companies do =
not like to be pressured to do stuff, so they tend to dislike activists. On=
e line of attack that corporate managers take against activists is to try t=
o limit their ability to quietly buy up big stakes in companies. Activists =
like to buy stakes quietly because, once they announce that they own a big =
chunk of stock in a company and plan to do activism, the stock will general=
ly go up.[8] If the rules said =E2=80=9Cas soon as an activist even thinks =
about buying stock, she has to disclose that, so everyone knows what she=E2=
=80=99s doing,=E2=80=9D then the stock will go up=C2=A0<em>before=C2=A0</em=
>she buys, and being an activist will be less economically viable. All of t=
he benefits of her activism =E2=80=94=C2=A0her ability to push the company =
to do better things for shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0will go, prospectively,=
 to the people who=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>her the stock, not to her.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right now the main rule about this in U.S. law i=
s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26067671.278641/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE1Lzc4bQ/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB453cd69e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">Section 13(d) of the Exchange Act</a>, which=
 says that investors have to disclose their stakes, and any activist intent=
ions, on Schedule 13D, within=C2=A010 days after they get above 5% of the s=
tock.=C2=A0This gives activists a chance to buy, you know, 8% or so of the =
stock quietly, before disclosing it 10 days after they cross the 5% thresho=
ld.=C2=A0(There is also Section 13(f), which says that institutional invest=
ment managers have to disclose all of their large positions every quarter.)=
 Corporate managers would prefer a shorter deadline to make life harder for=
 activists. (My old law firm, Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &amp; Katz, does a lo=
t of activism defense, and has been <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/26067671.278641/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2xyay5jb20vc2VjdGlvbi0xM=
y1kLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe7aef953" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">pushing for this</a> for=
 more than a decade.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Activists sometimes u=
se swaps to build larger economic positions without triggering 13D requirem=
ents, and so swap disclosure is a way to restrict activists. Right now, Sec=
tion 13(d) requires disclosure only of =E2=80=9Cbeneficial ownership=E2=80=
=9D of stock, and most swaps =E2=80=94 cash-settled bets on stock prices =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0do not carry beneficial ownership and don=E2=80=99t trigger =
disclosure requirements. Again, this fits with what the 13D rules are=C2=A0=
intended=C2=A0to do, which is require disclosure of big voting positions. B=
ut people worry that activists who buy stock on swap can quickly exchange t=
heir swaps for =E2=80=9Cphysical=E2=80=9D positions in voting stock. (For i=
nstance, by buying the stock from the bank that is holding it as a hedge to=
 their swap.) Or they worry that the activist=E2=80=99s swap counterparties=
 (the banks) will feel pressure to vote the stock the way the activist want=
s. Or they just want everyone to know that an activist is acquiring stock, =
on swap or otherwise, so that retail investors can copy the activists=E2=80=
=99 trades and make money while reducing the returns to activism.</p><table=
