, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SEC v. 10b5-1 plans</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/26067671.278641/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
cGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjEvbG9yZHN0b3duLWV4ZWN1dGl2ZXMtaGFkLWdvb2Q=
tdGltaW5nP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMTYyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3=
NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTIxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZ=
g/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd95c0260" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> basic issue</a> is that if yo=
u are a senior executive of a public company, (1) you always know things ab=
out the company that the public doesn=E2=80=99t know, but (2) we want you t=
o be able to trade stock anyway. Everyone loves when corporate executives=
=C2=A0<em>buy=C2=A0</em>stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0bullish signal, etc. =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and, since lots of executives are paid mostly in stock, we want them =
to be able to sell stock sometimes to buy houses and stuff.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">So there are rules and norms that let executives trade sto=
ck without getting in trouble for insider trading. One is the norm that the=
re are =E2=80=9Copen windows=E2=80=9D for trading, typically shortly after =
a company announces earnings; the idea is that the company has disclosed ev=
erything material in the earnings release and call, so now the executives d=
on=E2=80=99t know any more than anyone else and can trade freely. (This is =
mostly silly but nonetheless the norm.[9]) The other is <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26067671.278641/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3L=
mNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4xMGI1LTE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbaa=
56441" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">Rule 10b5-1(c)</a>, which says that if an executive sets up =
an automated=C2=A0<em>plan </em>to trade stock while she has no material no=
npublic information (i.e. when she is in an open window), that=C2=A0<em>pla=
n=C2=A0</em>can go ahead and trade stock for her even if she later gets som=
e material nonpublic information.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rule 10b5=
-1 plans are controversial. For one thing, it is <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26067671.278641/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDgvbW92aWVwYXNzLWNoYW5nZWQtc29tZS1=
wYXNzd29yZHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIxNjIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG=
1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMjE2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0d=
WZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB87795236" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> theoretically possible to g=
ame them</a> to insider trade in cute but somewhat silly ways.=C2=A0More im=
portant, though, nobody=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>believes that executives =
are ever free of inside information, so the whole 10b5-1 concept seems susp=
ect. If you set up a plan to trade stock, and then a week later you sell st=
ock, and then a week later bad news comes out and=C2=A0the stock goes down,=
 everyone will say =E2=80=9Cwell you probably had inside information didn=
=E2=80=99t you.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One really simple =
fix here would be to say: Okay, executives can trade stock all they want, b=
ut on a long delay. You can put in an order today saying =E2=80=9Csell 10,0=
00 shares,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Csell $50,000 of stock,=E2=80=9D and your br=
oker can execute it, but only=C2=A0<em>four months from now</em>. You might=
 have inside information today, and you might have inside information in fo=
ur months, but=C2=A0<em>it will definitely be different information</em>. I=
f you want to sell stock today because you have secret knowledge of a data =
breach or an earnings miss, or you want to buy stock today because you have=
 secret knowledge of a merger or an earnings beat, just put in the order to=
day, trade in four months, and by then the market will have already learned=
 and priced in whatever secret information you know today and moved on to o=
ther things.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The simple and elegant solutio=
n would be to have a new rule saying=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ccorporate executives can=
 put in an order to trade=C2=A0stock whenever they want, whether or not the=
y have inside information, but the order can=E2=80=99t execute for four mon=
ths and can=E2=80=99t be canceled in the meantime.=E2=80=9D But I guess tha=
t=E2=80=99s a bit harsh and weird, and anyway Rule 10b5-1 already exists, s=
o the SEC did not take that approach. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/26067671.278641/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXN=
zLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0yNTY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCad668c92" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Instead=
</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The proposed amendments t=
o Rule 10b5-1 would update the requirements for the affirmative defense, in=
cluding imposing a cooling off period before trading could commence under a=
 plan, prohibiting overlapping trading plans, and limiting single-trade pla=
ns to one trading plan per twelve month period. In addition, the proposed r=
ules would require directors and officers to furnish written certifications=
 that they are not aware of any material nonpublic information when they en=
ter into the plans and expand the existing good faith requirement for tradi=
ng under Rule 10b5-1 plans.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
=E2=80=9CSpecifically,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/26067671.278641/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9ydWxlcy9wcm9wb3NlZ=
C8yMDIxLzMzLTExMDEzLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8c4f8e9d" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">says t=
he SEC</a>, =E2=80=9Cour proposals would:=C2=A0Require a Rule 10b5-1 tradin=
g arrangement entered into by officers or directors to include a 120-day ma=
ndatory cooling-off period before any trading can commence under the tradin=
g arrangement after its adoption (including adoption of a modified trading =
arrangement).=E2=80=9D (The=C2=A0<em>company itself=C2=A0</em>can do a 10b5=
-1 plan, for a stock buyback, with a 30-day cooling-off period.) Seems reas=
onable.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are a bunch of other ne=
w 10b5-1 rules,[10]=C2=A0of which my favorite is the one that will =E2=80=
=9Cprovide that the affirmative defense under Rule 10b5-1(c)(1) does not ap=
ply to multiple overlapping Rule 10b5=E2=80=911 trading arrangements for op=
en market trades in the same class of securities.=E2=80=9D The classic cute=
sy securities-lawyer hypothetical way to game Rule 10b5-1 is:</p><ol style=
=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You don=E2=80=99t have inside information now,=
 but you are sure you will in five=C2=A0months. (For instance, you=E2=80=99=
ll announce earnings in 5.5 months; in five months you=E2=80=99ll know what=
=E2=80=99s in the earnings but the market won=E2=80=99t.)</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Set up a 10b5-1 plan, today, to sell a bunch of st=
ock in five months.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Set up another=
 10b5-1 plan, today, to buy a bunch of stock in five months.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Wait five months and get the inside information.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you have good inside informati=
on, cancel the selling plan but leave the buying one in place. You=E2=80=99=
ll buy stock, the information will come out, the stock will go up.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you have bad inside information, cancel=
 the buying plan but leave the selling one in place. You=E2=80=99ll sell st=
ock, the information will come out, the stock will go down.</li></ol><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea is that <em>canceling=C2=A0</em>a 10b5-1 pl=
an is not a =E2=80=9Ctrade=E2=80=9D and so you can do it even if you have i=
nside information. This is very cute but I cannot imagine anyone really doe=
s it, and I am pretty sure it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0illegal under existing law. No=
netheless the SEC is banning it just in case.</p><table class=3D"header" wi=
dth=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
